ly with Ankara's demands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://24.kg/obschestvo/60197_kakoy_privet_chinovniki_otreagirovali_nazayavlenie_turetskih_kolleg_osebate/|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0442... \u0427\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0430\u0433\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0443\u0440\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u043e \u00ab\u0421\u0435\u0431\u0430\u0442\u0435\u00bb|trans-title=As you salute... Officials react to the statement of Turkish colleagues on Sebat|date=15 August 2017|website=24|access-date=15 November 2017|language=Russian}}</ref>  In February 2017, the Turkish government announced that diplomas issued by the Ala-Too International University would no longer be valid in Turkey.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ilyasov|first1=Rustem|script-title=ru:\u0414\u0438\u043f\u043b\u043e\u043c\u044b \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430 \"\u0410\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044e\u0440\u043a-\u0410\u043b\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043e\" \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435 \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0446\u0438\u0438|trans-title=Diplomas of Ataturk Ala-Too University no longer accepted in Turkey|url=https://kloop.kg/blog/2017/02/04/diplomy-universiteta-atatyurk-alatoo-bolshe-ne-prinimayutsya-v-turtsii/|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=Kloop|date=4 February 2017|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, the name of the university was changed from the International Atat\u00fcrk-Alatoo University to the Ala-Too International University. The name of the organization that runs the Ala-Too International University along with 35 other schools and colleges was also changed from the Sebat Educational Foundation to the Sapat Educational Foundation. (''Sapat'' means quality in [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]].)\n\n== Academics ==\nThe Ala-Too International University has the following departments and programs:\n\n=== Faculty of New Technologies ===\n*  Computer science\n*  Electronics and nanoelectronics engineering\n*  Applied mathematics and IT\n\n=== Faculty of Social Sciences ===\n[[File:Main campus of IAAU.JPG|thumb|Main campus of the Ala-Too International University]]\n*  Turkology\n*  \u0421hineese language and translation\n*  Simultaneous translation\n*  English language and literature\n*  Pedagogy\n*  Psychology\n*  Journalism\n\n=== Faculty of Economics and Administrative Sciences ===\n*  World economy and international business\n*  International relations\n*  Management\n*  Finance and banking\n*  Law\n*  Accounting and audit\n*  Industrial engineering\n\n=== Faculty of Medicine ===\n[[File:IAAU Graduates, Class of 2011.JPG|thumb|right|Ala-Too International University graduation ceremony, Class of 2011]]\n*  General medicine\n*  Pediatrics\n\n=== Vocational Education ===\n*  Economy and accounting\n*  Banking\n*  Marketing\n*  Computer systems and complexes\n*  Software engineering\n*  Design\n*  Jurisprudence\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.iaau.edu.kg/ Official website] {{in lang|en|ru|ky}}\n*[http://www.alatoo.edu.kg/ Official website] {{in lang|en|ru|ky}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ala-Too International University}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Universities in Kyrgyzstan]]\n", "name_user": "Ismail.altinbilek", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ala-Too_International_University"}
{"title_page": "Jon Elster", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian social and political theorist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2018}}\n'''Jon Elster''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|l|s|t|\u0259r}}; born 22 February 1940, [[Oslo]]) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] social and [[political theorist]] who has authored works in the [[philosophy of social science]] and [[rational choice theory]]. He is also a notable proponent of [[analytical Marxism]], and a critic of [[neoclassical economics]] and [[public choice theory]], largely on behavioral and psychological grounds.\n\nIn 2016, he was awarded the 22nd [[Johan Skytte Prize in Political Science]] for his contributions to [[political science]].\n\n==Biography==\n{{BLP sources section|date=July 2018}}\nElster earned his PhD in 1972 from the [[Paris Descartes University]] in Paris with a dissertation on [[Karl Marx]]<ref>{{cite web| last =Yeghiayan| first =Eddie| title =JON ELSTER A Selected Bibliography| publisher =UCI Department of Philosophy| url =http://sun3.lib.uci.edu/~scctr/philosophy/elster.html| accessdate =2008-04-18| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://archive.today/20000816051346/http://sun3.lib.uci.edu/~scctr/philosophy/elster.html| archivedate =2000-08-16}}</ref> under the direction of [[Raymond Aron]].  Elster was a member of the [[September Group]] for many years but left in the early 1990s.  Elster previously taught at the [[University of Oslo]] in the department of history and held an endowed chair at the [[University of Chicago]], teaching in the departments of philosophy and political science. He is now Robert K. Merton Professor of Social Sciences with appointments in Political Science and Philosophy at [[Columbia University]] and ''professeur honoraire'' at the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France]]. He was awarded the [[Jean Nicod Prize]] in 1997 and the Skytte Prize in Political Science in 2016.\n\nHe is a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27639|title=Gruppe 3: Id\u00e9fag|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=28 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927170302/http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27639|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is also a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], of the [[American Philosophical Society]], of the [[Academia Europaea]], and a Corresponding [[Fellow of the British Academy]].\n\nHe is the son of journalist/author and CEO of the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]]  [[Torolf Elster]] and poet [[Magli Elster]].\n\nElster is doctor honoris causa at the universities of [[University of Valencia|Valencia]], [[Stockholm University|Stockholm]], [[University of Oslo|Oslo]], [[Norwegian University of Science and Technology|Trondheim (NTNU)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntnu.edu/phd/honorary-doctors|title=Honorary Doctors|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ntnu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>, [[Universit\u00e9 Catholique de Louvain|Louvain-la-Neuve]], [[Torcuato di Tella University|Torcuato di Tella]], and the [[National University of Colombia]]. He is honorary professor at the [[University of Chongqing]].\n\n==Philosophical work==\n{{BLP sources section|date=July 2018}}\nMuch of Elster's writing is characterized by attempts to use analytical theories, especially [[rational choice theory]], as a springboard for philosophical and ethical analysis, with numerous examples from literature and history. \"Elster has made important contributions to several fields,\" Daniel Little wrote in a review essay. \"The breadth and depth of his writings are striking in a time of high specialisation; he is read and discussed by political scientists, legal scholars, economists and philosophers. His work is difficult to summarise in a slogan, but ... it is generally informed by a broad and deep acquaintance with relevant literature in economics, political science, history, philosophy, and psychology.\"<ref>Chapter on Jon Elster by Daniel Little in ''New Horizons in Economic Thought: Appraisals of Leading Economists'', edited by Warren Samuels (Edward Elgar Publishing, 1992) {{ISBN|1-85278-379-6}}. Also available as download [http://www-personal.umd.umich.edu/~delittle/ELSTER3.PDF]</ref>\n\nA student of the philosophy of social science (a topic he investigated through case studies in ''Explaining Technical Change''), Elster strongly argued that social scientific explanations had to be built on top of [[methodological individualism]] (the belief that only individuals, not larger entities like \"organizations\" or \"societies\", can actually do things) and microfoundations (explaining big societal changes in terms of individual actions). He criticized Marxists and other social scientists for believing in [[Structural functionalism|functionalism]] (the belief that institutions exist because of their effect on society) and instead tried to give Marxism a foundation in [[game theory]] (the economic notion that people make choices based on the expected benefits and the choices others are likely to make).\n\nElster wrote numerous books attempting to use rational choice theory for a wide variety of social explanations. \"Rational choice theory is far more than a technical tool for explaining behaviour,\" he once wrote. \"It is also, and very importantly, a way of coming to grips with ourselves - not only what we should do, but even what we should be.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jon |last=Elster |title=Some unresolved problems in the theory of rational behaviour |journal=[[Acta Sociologica]] |year=1993 |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=179\u2013189 [p. 179] |doi=10.1177/000169939303600303 }}</ref> He attempted to apply it to topics as varied as politics (''Political Psychology''), bias and constrained preferences (''Sour Grapes''), emotions (''Alchemies of the Mind''), self-restraint (''Ulysses and the Sirens'', which was selected for the [[Norwegian Sociology Canon]]), Marxism (''[[Making Sense of Marx]]''), and more.\n\nIn doing so, he elucidated many issues with simplistic notions of rational choice: endogenous preference formation (certain actions today can change preferences tomorrow, so how does one decide which preferences one prefers?), framing (people express different preferences when the same question is asked different ways), imperfect rationality (weakness of the will, emotion, impulsiveness, habit, self-deception) and our adjustments for it, and [[time preference]]s, among others.\n\nAs time went on Elster began to sour on rational choice. A 1991 review in the ''[[London Review of Books]]'' noted \"Elster has lost his bearings, or at least his faith. [His latest books], he says, 'reflects an increasing disillusion with the power of reason'.\"<ref>[[Martin Hollis (philosopher)|Hollis, Martin]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20040516182619/http://www.geocities.com/hmelberg/elster/hollis91.htm Why Elster is stuck and needs to recover his faith], ''London Review of Books'', 13 January 1991</ref> His magisterial 500-page book ''Explaining Social Behavior'' includes something of a recantation:\n\n{{Quote|I now believe that rational-choice theory has less explanatory power than I used to think. Do real people act on the calculations that make up many pages of mathematical appendixes in leading journals? I do not think so. ... ''There is no general nonintentional mechanism that can simulate or mimic rationality.'' ... At the same time, the empirical support ... tends to be quite weak. This is of course a sweeping statement. ... let me simply point out the high level of disagreement among competent scholars ... fundamental, persistent disagreements among 'schools.' We ''never'' observe the kind of many-decimal-points precision that would put controversy to rest.<ref>''Explaining Social Behaviour'', pp. 5, 25ff</ref>}}\n\nThe book discusses both rational behavior, but also irrational behavior, which Elster says is \"widespread and frequent [but] not inevitable ... we ''want'' to be rational\".<ref>''Explaining Social Behaviour'', p. 232</ref> A more recent book, ''Le d\u00e9sint\u00e9ressement'' (part of a two-volume ''Trait\u00e9 critique de l\u2019homme \u00e9conomique''), explores the ramifications of these insights for the possibility of disinterested action.<ref>Review of ''Le d\u00e9sint\u00e9ressement'', by [[Gloria Origgi]], [http://berlinbooks.org/brb/2010/01/origgi-desinteressement/ The Possibility of Disinterested Action], The Berlin Review of Books, 8 January 2010.</ref>\n\n== Selected writings ==\n* ''Leibniz et la formation de l'esprit capitaliste'' (Paris, 1975) {{ISBN|2-7007-0018-X}}\n* ''Leibniz and the development of economic rationality'' (Oslo, 1975)\n* ''Logic and Society'' (New York, 1978)\n* ''Ulysses and the Sirens'' (Cambridge, 1979)\n* \"Sour grapes - studies in the subversion of rationality\" in {{cite book | editor-last1 = Sen | editor-first1 = Amartya | editor-last2 = Williams | editor-first2 = Bernard | editor-link1 = Amartya Sen | editor-link2 = Bernard Williams | title = Utilitarianism and beyond | pages = 219\u2013238 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge | year = 1982 | isbn = 9780511611964 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n* ''Explaining Technical Change : a Case Study in the Philosophy of Science'' (Oslo, 1983)\n* {{cite book | url= | isbn=978-0521297059 | author=Jon Elster | authormask=0 | title=[[Making Sense of Marx]] | location=Cambridge | publisher=Cambridge University Press | series=Studies in Marxism and Social Theory | year=1985 }} \n* ''[[An Introduction to Karl Marx]]'' (Cambridge, 1986)\n* ''The Cement of Society: A study of social order'' (Cambridge, 1989)\n* ''Solomonic Judgments: Studies in the limitation of rationality'' (Cambridge, 1989)\n* ''Nuts and Bolts for the Social Sciences'' (Cambridge, 1989)\n* ''Local Justice: How institutions allocate scarce goods and necessary burdens'' (New York, 1992)\n* ''Political Psychology'' (Cambridge, 1993)\n* ''The Ethics of Medical Choice'' (with Nicolas Herpin; London, 1994)\n* ''Strong Feelings: Emotion, Addiction, and Human Behavior'' (Cambridge, 1999)\n* ''Alchemies of the Mind: Rationality and the Emotions'' (Cambridge, 1999)\n* ''Ulysses Unbound: Studies in Rationality, Precommitment, and Constraints'' (Cambridge, 2000)\n* ''Closing the Books: Transitional Justice in Historical Perspective'' (Cambridge, 2004)\n* ''Explaining Social Behavior: More Nuts and Bolts for the Social Sciences'' (Cambridge, 2007; revised ed. 2015)\n* ''Reason and Rationality'' (Princeton, 2009)\n* ''Alexis de Tocqueville: The First Social Scientist'' (Cambridge, 2009)\n*''Le d\u00e9sint\u00e9ressemen''t (Paris, 2009)\n*''L'irrationalit\u00e9'' (Paris,  2010)\n*''Securities against Misrule. Juries, Assemblies, Elections'' (Cambridge, 2013) {{ISBN|9781107649958}}\n*''Constituent Assemblies'' (edited with Roberto Gargarella, Vatsal Naresh and [[Bj\u00f8rn Erik Rasch]]; Cambridge, 2019)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[G. A. Cohen]]\n* [[John Roemer]]\n* [[Jean Nicod Prize|List of Jean Nicod Prize laureates]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080405234307/http://www.geocities.com/hmelberg/elster/elster.htm Elster page] at [[Columbia University Department of Philosophy]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061116020557/http://www.college-de-france.fr/default/EN/all/rat_soc/index.htm Elster page] at the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France]]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405234307/http://www.geocities.com/hmelberg/elster/elster.htm |date=April 5, 2008 |title=Jon Elster page maintained by Hans O. Melberg }}\n*[http://www.users.globalnet.co.uk/~rxv/books/elster.htm Selected quotes by Jon Elster]\n*{{worldcat id|id=lccn-n79-22962}}\n*[http://www.laviedesidees.fr/When-the-lottery-is-fairer-than.html When the lottery is fairer than rational choice. Interview with Jon Elster] (text&video), laviedesidees.fr, 26/11/2008\n\n{{September group}}\n{{John von Neumann Award recipients}}{{Recipients of the Johan Skytte Prize in Political Science}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elster, Jon}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Coll\u00e8ge de France faculty]]\n[[Category:Norwegian philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian political philosophers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Jean Nicod Prize laureates]]\n[[Category:Members of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n[[Category:Rationality theorists]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of social science]]\n[[Category:Corresponding Fellows of the British Academy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Norwegian social and political theorist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2018}}\n'''Jon Elster''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|l|s|t|\u0259r}}; born 22 February 1940, [[Oslo]]) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] social and [[political theorist]] who has authored works in the [[philosophy of social science]] and [[rational choice theory]]. He is also a notable proponent of [[analytical Marxism]], and a critic of [[neoclassical economics]] and [[public choice theory]], largely on behavioral and psychological grounds.\n\nIn 2016, he was awarded the 22nd [[Johan Skytte Prize in Political Science]] for his contributions to [[political science]].\n\n==Biography==\n{{BLP sources section|date=July 2018}}\nElster earned his PhD in 1972 from the [[Paris Descartes University]] in Paris with a dissertation on [[Karl Marx]]<ref>{{cite web| last =Yeghiayan| first =Eddie| title =JON ELSTER A Selected Bibliography| publisher =UCI Department of Philosophy| url =http://sun3.lib.uci.edu/~scctr/philosophy/elster.html| accessdate =2008-04-18| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://archive.today/20000816051346/http://sun3.lib.uci.edu/~scctr/philosophy/elster.html| archivedate =2000-08-16}}</ref> under the direction of [[Raymond Aron]].  Elster was a member of the [[September Group]] for many years but left in the early 1990s.  Elster previously taught at the [[University of Oslo]] in the department of history and held an endowed chair at the [[University of Chicago]], teaching in the departments of philosophy and political science. He is now Robert K. Merton Professor of Social Sciences with appointments in Political Science and Philosophy at [[Columbia University]] and ''professeur honoraire'' at the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France]]. He was awarded the [[Jean Nicod Prize]] in 1997 and the Skytte Prize in Political Science in 2016.\n\nHe is a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27639|title=Gruppe 3: Id\u00e9fag|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=28 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927170302/http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27639|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is also a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], of the [[American Philosophical Society]], of the [[Academia Europaea]], and a Corresponding [[Fellow of the British Academy]].\n\nHe is the son of journalist/author and CEO of the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]]  [[Torolf Elster]] and poet [[Magli Elster]].\n\nElster is doctor honoris causa at the universities of [[University of Valencia|Valencia]], [[Stockholm University|Stockholm]], [[University of Oslo|Oslo]], [[Norwegian University of Science and Technology|Trondheim (NTNU)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntnu.edu/phd/honorary-doctors|title=Honorary Doctors|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ntnu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>, [[Universit\u00e9 Catholique de Louvain|Louvain-la-Neuve]], [[Torcuato di Tella University|Torcuato di Tella]], and the [[National University of Colombia]]. He is honorary professor at the [[University of Chongqing]].\n\n==Philosophical work==\n{{BLP sources section|date=July 2018}}\nMuch of Elster's writing is characterized by attempts to use analytical theories, especially [[rational choice theory]], as a springboard for philosophical and ethical analysis, with numerous examples from literature and history. \"Elster has made important contributions to several fields,\" Daniel Little wrote in a review essay. \"The breadth and depth of his writings are striking in a time of high specialisation; he is read and discussed by political scientists,legal scholars, economists and philosophers. His work is difficult to summarise in a slogan, but ... it is generally informed by a broad and deep acquaintance with relevant literature in economics, political science, history, philosophy, and psychology.\"<ref>Chapter on Jon Elster by Daniel Little in ''New Horizons in Economic Thought: Appraisals of Leading Economists'', edited by Warren Samuels (Edward Elgar Publishing, 1992) {{ISBN|1-85278-379-6}}. Also available as download [http://www-personal.umd.umich.edu/~delittle/ELSTER3.PDF]</ref>\n\nA student of the philosophy of social science (a topic he investigated through case studies in ''Explaining Technical Change''), Elster strongly argued that social scientific explanations had to be built on top of [[methodological individualism]] (the belief that only individuals, not larger entities like \"organizations\" or \"societies\", can actually do things) and microfoundations (explaining big societal changes in terms of individual actions). He criticized Marxists and other social scientists for believing in [[Structural functionalism|functionalism]] (the belief that institutions exist because of their effect on society) and instead tried to give Marxism a foundation in [[game theory]] (the economic notion that people make choices based on the expected benefits and the choices others are likely to make).\n\nElster wrote numerous books attempting to use rational choice theory for a wide variety of social explanations. \"Rational choice theory is far more than a technical tool for explaining behaviour,\" he once wrote. \"It is also, and very importantly, a way of coming to grips with ourselves - not only what we should do, but even what we should be.\"<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jon |last=Elster |title=Some unresolved problems in the theory of rational behaviour |journal=[[Acta Sociologica]] |year=1993 |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=179\u2013189 [p. 179] |doi=10.1177/000169939303600303 }}</ref> He attempted to apply it to topics as varied as politics (''Political Psychology''), bias and constrained preferences (''Sour Grapes''), emotions (''Alchemies of the Mind''), self-restraint (''Ulysses and the Sirens'', which was selected for the [[Norwegian Sociology Canon]]), Marxism (''[[Making Sense of Marx]]''), and more.\n\nIn doing so, he elucidated many issues with simplistic notions of rational choice: endogenous preference formation (certain actions today can change preferences tomorrow, so how does one decide which preferences one prefers?), framing (people express different preferences when the same question is asked different ways), imperfect rationality (weakness of the will, emotion, impulsiveness, habit, self-deception) and our adjustments for it, and [[time preference]]s, among others.\n\nAs time went on Elster began to sour on rational choice. A 1991 review in the ''[[London Review of Books]]'' noted \"Elster has lost his bearings, or at least his faith. [His latest books], he says, 'reflects an increasing disillusion with the power of reason'.\"<ref>[[Martin Hollis (philosopher)|Hollis, Martin]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20040516182619/http://www.geocities.com/hmelberg/elster/hollis91.htm Why Elster is stuck and needs to recover his faith], ''London Review of Books'', 13 January 1991</ref> His magisterial 500-page book ''Explaining Social Behavior'' includes something of a recantation:\n\n{{Quote|I now believe that rational-choice theory has less explanatory power than I used to think. Do real people act on the calculations that make up many pages of mathematical appendixes in leading journals? I do not think so. ... ''There is no general nonintentional mechanism that can simulate or mimic rationality.'' ... At the same time, the empirical support ... tends to be quite weak. This is of course a sweeping statement. ... let me simply point out the high level of disagreement among competent scholars ... fundamental, persistent disagreements among 'schools.' We ''never'' observe the kind of many-decimal-points precision that would put controversy to rest.<ref>''Explaining Social Behaviour'', pp. 5, 25ff</ref>}}\n\nThe book discusses both rational behavior, but also irrational behavior, which Elster says is \"widespread and frequent [but] not inevitable ... we ''want'' to be rational\".<ref>''Explaining Social Behaviour'', p. 232</ref> A more recent book, ''Le d\u00e9sint\u00e9ressement'' (part of a two-volume ''Trait\u00e9 critique de l\u2019homme \u00e9conomique''), explores the ramifications of these insights for the possibility of disinterested action.<ref>Review of ''Le d\u00e9sint\u00e9ressement'', by [[Gloria Origgi]], [http://berlinbooks.org/brb/2010/01/origgi-desinteressement/ The Possibility of Disinterested Action], The Berlin Review of Books, 8 January 2010.</ref>\n\n== Selected writings ==\n* ''Leibniz et la formation de l'esprit capitaliste'' (Paris, 1975) {{ISBN|2-7007-0018-X}}\n* ''Leibniz and the development of economic rationality'' (Oslo, 1975)\n* ''Logic and Society'' (New York, 1978)\n* ''Ulysses and the Sirens'' (Cambridge, 1979)\n* \"Sour grapes - studies in the subversion of rationality\" in {{cite book | editor-last1 = Sen | editor-first1 = Amartya | editor-last2 = Williams | editor-first2 = Bernard | editor-link1 = Amartya Sen | editor-link2 = Bernard Williams | title = Utilitarianism and beyond | pages = 219\u2013238 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge | year = 1982 | isbn = 9780511611964 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n* ''Explaining Technical Change : a Case Study in the Philosophy of Science'' (Oslo, 1983)\n* {{cite book | url= | isbn=978-0521297059 | author=Jon Elster | authormask=0 | title=[[Making Sense of Marx]] | location=Cambridge | publisher=Cambridge University Press | series=Studies in Marxism and Social Theory | year=1985 }} \n* ''[[An Introduction to Karl Marx]]'' (Cambridge, 1986)\n* ''The Cement of Society: A study of social order'' (Cambridge, 1989)\n* ''Solomonic Judgments: Studies in the limitation of rationality'' (Cambridge, 1989)\n* ''Nuts and Bolts for the Social Sciences'' (Cambridge, 1989)\n* ''Local Justice: How institutions allocate scarce goods and necessary burdens'' (New York, 1992)\n* ''Political Psychology'' (Cambridge, 1993)\n* ''The Ethics of Medical Choice'' (with Nicolas Herpin; London, 1994)\n* ''Strong Feelings: Emotion, Addiction, and Human Behavior'' (Cambridge, 1999)\n* ''Alchemies of the Mind: Rationality and the Emotions'' (Cambridge, 1999)\n* ''Ulysses Unbound: Studies in Rationality, Precommitment, and Constraints'' (Cambridge, 2000)\n* ''Closing the Books: Transitional Justice in Historical Perspective'' (Cambridge, 2004)\n* ''Explaining Social Behavior: More Nuts and Bolts for the Social Sciences'' (Cambridge, 2007; revised ed. 2015)\n* ''Reason and Rationality'' (Princeton, 2009)\n* ''Alexis de Tocqueville: The First Social Scientist'' (Cambridge, 2009)\n*''Le d\u00e9sint\u00e9ressemen''t (Paris, 2009)\n*''L'irrationalit\u00e9'' (Paris,  2010)\n*''Securities against Misrule. Juries, Assemblies, Elections'' (Cambridge, 2013) {{ISBN|9781107649958}}\n*''Constituent Assemblies'' (edited with Roberto Gargarella, Vatsal Naresh and [[Bj\u00f8rn Erik Rasch]]; Cambridge, 2019)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[G. A. Cohen]]\n* [[John Roemer]]\n* [[Jean Nicod Prize|List of Jean Nicod Prize laureates]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080405234307/http://www.geocities.com/hmelberg/elster/elster.htm Elster page] at [[Columbia University Department of Philosophy]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061116020557/http://www.college-de-france.fr/default/EN/all/rat_soc/index.htm Elster page] at the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France]]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405234307/http://www.geocities.com/hmelberg/elster/elster.htm |date=April 5, 2008 |title=Jon Elster page maintained by Hans O. Melberg }}\n*[http://www.users.globalnet.co.uk/~rxv/books/elster.htm Selected quotes by Jon Elster]\n*{{worldcat id|id=lccn-n79-22962}}\n*[http://www.laviedesidees.fr/When-the-lottery-is-fairer-than.html When the lottery is fairer than rational choice. Interview with Jon Elster] (text&video), laviedesidees.fr, 26/11/2008\n\n{{September group}}\n{{John von Neumann Award recipients}}{{Recipients of the Johan Skytte Prize in Political Science}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elster, Jon}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Coll\u00e8ge de France faculty]]\n[[Category:Norwegian philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian political philosophers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Jean Nicod Prize laureates]]\n[[Category:Members of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n[[Category:Rationality theorists]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of social science]]\n[[Category:Corresponding Fellows of the British Academy]]\n", "name_user": "Poppopsun", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePhilosophical work", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Elster"}
{"title_page": "Kevin McKeown (politician)", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name            = Kevin McKeown\n| image           = Headshot of Santa Monica, CA, Mayor Kevin McKeown.jpg \n|caption= McKeown at Santa Monica City Hall\n| office           = Mayor of the City of [[Santa Monica]]\n| term_start      = December 10, 2019\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1948|1|6}}\n|birth_place= [[Bronxville, New York]], U.S.\n|residence=Wilmont neighborhood, [[Santa Monica]], U.S.|party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|website={{url|http://www.mckeown.net}}\n}}\n'''Kevin McKeown''' is the Mayor of Santa Monica.<ref>https://www.smgov.net/departments/council/content.aspx?id=13705</ref>  This is the second time he has served as Mayor (his first term was in 2015).  He has been elected to the Santa Monica City Council six times.<ref>https://www.surfsantamonica.com/ssm_site/the_lookout/news/News-2019/December-2019/12_11_2019_McKeown_Assumes_Post_as_Santa_Monica_Mayor.html</ref>  He is also a multi-term elected delegate to the Central Committee of the California Democratic Party.<ref>https://www.cadem.org/our-party/adem/body/AD50-results-2.pdf</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nKevin McKeown was born just north of New York City.  His family moved to New Haven, CT, where he graduated from public high school at 16 and subsequently attended Yale.  He was active at campus radio station WYBC, beginning a career path that eventually led him to move to Santa Monica and become general manager of Los Angeles station KROQ in the late 70s.<ref>https://www.440int.com/namesm2a.html#_kmckeo</ref>\n\nMcKeown has now been a Santa Monica renter for almost 45 years.  After leaving radio and advertising, he worked for 25 years as Macintosh computer and educational technology consultant for the Santa Monica-Malibu Unified School District.<ref>https://www.smgov.net/departments/council/content.aspx?id=2383</ref>\n\nMcKeown served on SMMUSD's technology advisory committee, the City of Santa Monica\u2019s Telecommunications Working\u00a0Group, the steering committee of Santa Monicans for Renters\u2019 Rights, and as chair of\u00a0the Wilshire/Montana Neighborhood Coalition, before first being elected to City Council in 1998.<ref>http://www.mckeown.net/Bio_-_Santa_Monica_Councilmember_Kevin_McKeown.html</ref>\n\n==Career as an elected official==\n\nNow in his sixth term on the City Council, including time as Santa Monica\u2019s Mayor, McKeown focuses on affordable housing, workers\u2019 rights, and environmental sustainability. During his first term as Mayor of Santa Monica, he was an invited presenter at the COP21 United Nations Climate Change Conference in Paris.<ref>https://www.smdp.com/mckeown-joins-national-mayors-call-climate-change-action/148817</ref><ref>https://www.bigbluebus.com/Newsroom/Press/Mayor-McKeown-to-Present-Santa-Monica\u2019s-Ambitious-Climate--Action-Project-and-Progress-at-Paris-Climate-Summit.aspx</ref>  He is a long-standing advocate for single-payer health care.<ref>https://www.laprogressive.com/single-payer-hr-676-would-save-mone/</ref>\n  \nMcKeown represents Santa Monica on the\u00a0Westside Cities Council of Governments<ref>https://www.westsidecities.org/boardmembers</ref>, on the\u00a0Santa Monica Bay Restoration Commission<ref>https://www.smbrc.ca.gov/about_us/orientation/docs/gb_mbrs_1912.pdf</ref>, and as chair of the Energy Committee on the Board of the\u00a0Clean Power Alliance<ref>https://cleanpoweralliance.org/get-involved/board-administration/</ref>, a regional community choice utility bringing 100% renewably sourced electricity to Santa Monica.<ref>https://climateactionsantamonica.org/2019/01/07/100-clean-power-is-coming-to-you-santa-monica/</ref>\n\u00a0 \nMcKeown holds dual citizenship with the United States (by birth) and the Republic of Ireland (by descent).  He is vice chair of the Irish-American Caucus of the California Democratic Party.<ref>https://myemail.constantcontact.com/Saturday-November-17th-Fall-Executive-Board-Irish-American-Caucus-Meeting.html?soid=1105231108874&aid=2LgbtmcY3KM&fbclid=IwAR3kbHlh8ZbBaWb05VnGD0eX_5qri37D17j-pGPabLPBSPi4Zs2nR64KoNE</ref>  He has twice (2010 and 2013) been named California Assembly District Democrat of the Year for the Santa Monica area.<ref>https://smmirror.com/2013/10/santa-monica-councilman-kevin-mckeown-named-democrat-of-the-year/</ref>\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name            = Kevin McKeown\n| image           = Headshot of Santa Monica, CA, Mayor Kevin McKeown.jpg \n|caption= McKeown at Santa Monica City Hall\n| office           = Mayor of the City of [[Santa Monica]]\n| term_start      = December 10, 2019\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1948|1|6}}\n|birth_place= [[Bronxville, New York]], U.S.\n|residence=Wilmont neighborhood, [[Santa Monica]], U.S.|party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|website={{url|http://www.mckeown.net}}\n}}\n'''Kevin McKeown''' is the Mayor of Santa Monica.<ref>https://www.smgov.net/departments/council/content.aspx?id=13705</ref>  This is the second time he has served as Mayor (his first term was in 2015).  He has been elected to the Santa Monica City Council six times.<ref>https://www.surfsantamonica.com/ssm_site/the_lookout/news/News-2019/December-2019/12_11_2019_McKeown_Assumes_Post_as_Santa_Monica_Mayor.html</ref>  He is also a multi-term elected delegate to the Central Committee of the California Democratic Party.<ref>https://www.cadem.org/our-party/adem/body/AD50-results-2.pdf</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nKevin McKeown was born just north of New York City.  His family moved to New Haven, CT, where he graduated from public high school at 16 and won a full scholarship to Yale.  He became deeply involved in campus radio station WYBC, beginning a career path that eventually led him to move to Santa Monica and become general manager of Los Angeles station KROQ in the late 70s.<ref>https://www.440int.com/namesm2a.html#_kmckeo</ref>\n\nMcKeown has now been a Santa Monica renter for almost 45 years.  After leaving radio and advertising, he worked for 25 years as Macintosh computer and educational technology consultant for the Santa Monica-Malibu Unified School District.<ref>https://www.smgov.net/departments/council/content.aspx?id=2383</ref>\n\nMcKeown served on SMMUSD's technology advisory committee, the City of Santa Monica\u2019s Telecommunications Working\u00a0Group, the steering committee of Santa Monicans for Renters\u2019 Rights, and as chair of\u00a0the Wilshire/Montana Neighborhood Coalition, before first being elected to City Council in 1998.<ref>http://www.mckeown.net/Bio_-_Santa_Monica_Councilmember_Kevin_McKeown.html</ref>\n\n==Career as an elected official==\n\nNow in his sixth term on the City Council, including time as Santa Monica\u2019s Mayor, McKeown focuses on affordable housing, workers\u2019 rights, and environmental sustainability. During his first term as Mayor of Santa Monica, he was an invited presenter at the COP21 United Nations Climate Change Conference in Paris.<ref>https://www.smdp.com/mckeown-joins-national-mayors-call-climate-change-action/148817</ref><ref>https://www.bigbluebus.com/Newsroom/Press/Mayor-McKeown-to-Present-Santa-Monica\u2019s-Ambitious-Climate--Action-Project-and-Progress-at-Paris-Climate-Summit.aspx</ref>  He is a long-standing advocate for single-payer health care.<ref>https://www.laprogressive.com/single-payer-hr-676-would-save-mone/</ref>\n  \nMcKeown represents Santa Monica on the\u00a0Westside Cities Council of Governments<ref>https://www.westsidecities.org/boardmembers</ref>, on the\u00a0Santa Monica Bay Restoration Commission<ref>https://www.smbrc.ca.gov/about_us/orientation/docs/gb_mbrs_1912.pdf</ref>, and as chair of the Energy Committee on the Board of the\u00a0Clean Power Alliance<ref>https://cleanpoweralliance.org/get-involved/board-administration/</ref>, a regional community choice utility bringing 100% renewably sourced electricity to Santa Monica.<ref>https://climateactionsantamonica.org/2019/01/07/100-clean-power-is-coming-to-you-santa-monica/</ref>\n\u00a0 \nMcKeown holds dual citizenship with the United States (by birth) and the Republic of Ireland (by descent).  He is vice chair of the Irish-American Caucus of the California Democratic Party.<ref>https://myemail.constantcontact.com/Saturday-November-17th-Fall-Executive-Board-Irish-American-Caucus-Meeting.html?soid=1105231108874&aid=2LgbtmcY3KM&fbclid=IwAR3kbHlh8ZbBaWb05VnGD0eX_5qri37D17j-pGPabLPBSPi4Zs2nR64KoNE</ref>  He has twice (2010 and 2013) been named California Assembly District Democrat of the Year for the Santa Monica area.<ref>https://smmirror.com/2013/10/santa-monica-councilman-kevin-mckeown-named-democrat-of-the-year/</ref>\n", "name_user": "CrepticRotrusion", "label": "safe", "comment": "simplified background section, increased clarity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_McKeown_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Cumberland (UK Parliament constituency)", "text_new": "{{short description|Parliamentary constituency in the United Kingdom, 1801\u20131832}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency\n|name       = Cumberland\n|type       = County\n|parliament = uk\n|year       = 1290\n|abolished  = 1832\n|elects_howmany = two\n|previous   = \n|next       = [[Cumberland East (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland East]] and [[Cumberland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland West]]\n|}}\n\n'''Cumberland''' is a former [[United Kingdom]] [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliamentary]] [[constituency]]. It was a [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] of the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of England]] then of the [[Parliament of Great Britain]] from 1707 to 1800 and of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] from 1801 to 1832. It was represented by two [[Knights of the Shire]]. It was divided between the constituencies of [[Cumberland East (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland East]] and [[Cumberland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland West]] in 1832.\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n* ''Constituency created 1290''\n\n===MPs 1290\u20131640===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Parliament!!First member!!Second member\n|-\n| 1301|| [[John Wigton|Sir John Wigton]]||\n|-\n| 1305|| [[John Wigton|Sir John Wigton]]||\n|-\n| 1306|| [[John de Lucy|Sir John de Lucy]]||\n|-\n| 1312|| [[Andrew Harclay, 1st Earl of Carlisle|Andrew Harclay]]||\n|-\n| 1313|| [[John Wigton|Sir John Wigton]]||\n|-\n| 1316|| [[John de Skelton]]||\n|-\n| 1324|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]||\n|-\n| 1325||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1327||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1328||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1331||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1332||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1337|| [[Thomas de Skelton]]||\n|-\n| 1342|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]||[[Peter de Tylliol]]\n|-\n| 1344|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]||[[John de Orreton]]\n|-\n| 1345|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]|| [[Henry de Malton]]\n|-\n| 1368|| [[James Pickering]]||\n|-\n| 1377|| [[Richard de Sandys]] ||Sir [[Richard Moubray]]\n|-\n| 1377|| [[John FitzHugh de Lowther]]||\n|-\n| 1378|| [[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Peter Tilliol]]\n|-\n| 1380 (Jan)|| [[William Curwen|Sir William Curwen]]\n|-\n| 1380 (Nov)|| [[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Peter Tilliol]]\n|-\n| 1383|| [[John de Burgham]] ||[[John de Kirby]]\n|-\n| 1385|| [[Richard de Beaulieu|Sir Richard de Beaulieu]]||[[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]\n|-\n| 1386||[[Amand Monceaux]]|| [[John Thirlwall]] <ref name = HoP1>{{cite web | url= http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/constituencies/cumberland|title= History of Parliament| accessdate = 2011-09-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1388 (Feb)|| [[John de Derwentwater|Sir John de Derwentwater]]|| [[John Ireby|Sir John Ireby]] <ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1388 (Sep)|| [[Amand Monceaux]]|| [[Robert Muncaster|Sir Robert Muncaster]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1390 (Jan)|| [[Amand Monceaux]]|| [[William de Threlkeld]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1390 (Nov)|| [[William Stapleton (died 1432)|William Stapleton]]|| [[Thomas Sands (MP)|Thomas Sands]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1391||[[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[Robert Lowther (died 1430)|Robert Lowther]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1393||[[Geoffrey Tilliol]]|| [[William Lowther (died c.1421)|William Lowther]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1394||[[Clement Skelton|Sir Clement Skelton]]|| [[Robert Lowther (died 1430)|Robert Lowther]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1395||[[William Stapleton (died 1432)|William Stapleton]]|| [[Thomas Sands (MP)|Thomas Sands]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1397 (Jan)|| [[John Ireby|Sir John Ireby]]|| [[Clement Skelton|Sir Clement Skelton]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1397 (Sep)|| [[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[William Osmundlaw]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1399||[[William Leigh (MP)|Sir William Leigh]]|| [[Roland Vaux]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1401||[[Robert Lowther (died 1430)|Robert Lowther]]|| [[William Stapleton (died 1432)|William Stapleton]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1402|| [[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[John Skelton (died 1439)|John Skelton]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1404 (Jan)|| [[Robert Lowther (died 1430)|Sir Robert Lowther]]|| [[William Lowther (died c.1421)|William Lowther I]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1404 (Oct)|| [[John More (MP for Cumberland)|John More I]]|| [[William Bewley (MP)|William Bewley]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1406||[[Robert Lowther (died 1430)|Sir Robert Lowther]]|| [[John Skelton (died 1439)|Sir John Skelton]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1407||[[William Stapleton (died 1432)|William Stapleton]]|| [[William More (died 1434)|William More]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1410||[[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[Christopher Moresby]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1411||||\n|-\t\n| 1413 (Feb)||\n|-\n| 1413 (May)|| [[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[William Bewley (MP)|William Bewley]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1414 (Apr)|| [[Robert Lowther (died 1430)|(Sir) Robert Lowther]]|| [[William Leigh (MP)|Sir William Leigh]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1414 (Nov)|| [[Christopher Curwen (MP)|Sir Christopher Curwen]]|| [[John Eaglesfield]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1415||\n|-\t\n| 1416 (Mar)|| [[John Lancaster (died 1434)|(Sir) John Lancaster]]|| [[William Stapleton (died 1432)|William Stapleton]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1416 (Oct)||\n|-\n| 1417||[[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[Robert Lowther (died 1430)|(Sir) Robert Lowther]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1419||[[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[Richard Restwold (died c.1423)|Richard Restwold I]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1420||[[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]|| [[Thomas More (died 1461)|Thomas More]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1421 (May)|| [[John Lamplugh|Sir John Lamplugh]]|| [[Richard Restwold (died 1475)|Richard Restwold II]]<ref name = HoP1/>\n|-\n| 1421 (Dec)|| [[Peter