seph Pennington, 2nd Baronet|Sir Joseph Pennington, Bt]] ||\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" rowspan=\"6\" |\n|1745\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Sir John Pennington, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Pennington, Bt]] || rowspan=\"6\"|\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n|1755\n|[[Sir William Lowther, 3rd Baronet|Sir William Lowther, Bt]] ||\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n|1756\n|[[Sir William Fleming, 3rd Baronet|Sir William Fleming]] ||\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n|1757\n|[[James Lowther, 1st Earl of Lonsdale|Sir James Lowther, Bt]] ||\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n|1761\n|[[Sir Wilfrid Lawson, 8th Baronet|Sir Wilfrid Lawson, Bt]] ||\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n|1762\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[James Lowther, 1st Earl of Lonsdale|Sir James Lowther, Bt]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[British Tory Party|Tory]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}}\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n|March 1768\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Henry Curwen (died 1778)|Henry Curwen]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}}\" rowspan=\"5\" |\n|December 1768\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Sir Henry Fletcher, 1st Baronet, of Clea|Sir Henry Fletcher, Bt]] <ref>At the general election of 1768, Lowther defeated Fletcher by two votes, but on petition the result was overturned and Fletcher declared elected</ref>|| rowspan=\"5\"|[[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1774\n|[[James Lowther, 1st Earl of Lonsdale|Sir James Lowther, Bt]] ||[[British Tory Party|Tory]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1784\n|[[William Lowther, 1st Earl of Lonsdale|Sir William Lowther, Bt]] || [[British Tory Party|Tory]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1790\n|[[Humphrey Senhouse (politician)|Humphrey Senhouse]] ||[[British Tory Party|Tory]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" rowspan=\"4\" |\n|1796\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Sir John Lowther, 1st Baronet, of Swillington|John Lowther]] <ref>Created a baronet as Sir John Lowther, 1824</ref>|| rowspan=\"4\"|[[British Tory Party|Tory]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Tories (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1806\n|[[George Howard, 6th Earl of Carlisle|Viscount Morpeth]] || [[British Tory Party|Tory]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1820\n|[[John Christian Curwen]] || [[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}}\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n|1829\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Sir James Graham, 2nd Baronet|Sir James Graham, Bt]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |\n|1831\n|[[William Blamire]] ||[[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]]\n|}\n*''Constituency abolished'' (1832)\n\n'''Notes'''\n<references/>\n\n==Elections==\n\nThe county franchise, from 1430, was held by the adult male owners of freehold land valued at 40 shillings or more. Each elector had as many votes as there were seats to be filled. Votes had to be cast by a spoken declaration, in public, at the [[hustings]], which took place in the town of [[Cockermouth]]. The expense and difficulty of voting at only one location in the county, together with the lack of a secret ballot contributed to the corruption and intimidation of electors, which was widespread in the unreformed British political system.\n\nThe expense, to candidates, of contested elections encouraged the leading families of the county to agree on the candidates to be returned unopposed whenever possible. Contested county elections were therefore unusual.\n\n==Election results==\n{{Expand section|date=September 2008}}\n\n''Election results taken from the History of Parliament Trust series.''\n\n===Elections in the 18th century===\n\n{{Election box begin |\n |title=[[1715 British general election|General election 1715]]: Cumberland (2 seats)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Non Partisan\n |candidate = '''[[Sir James Lowther, 4th Baronet|James Lowther]]'''\n |votes = Unopposed\n |percentage = ''N/A''\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Non Partisan\n |candidate = '''[[Sir Gilfrid Lawson, 6th Baronet|Gilfrid Lawson]]'''\n |votes = Unopposed\n |percentage = ''N/A''\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |\n |title=[[1722 British general election|General election 1722]]: Cumberland (2 seats)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Non Partisan\n |candidate = '''[[Sir Christopher Musgrave, 5th Baronet|Christopher Musgrave]]'''\n |votes = Unopposed\n |percentage = ''N/A''\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Non Partisan\n |candidate = '''[[Sir Gilfrid Lawson, 6th Baronet|Gilfrid Lawson]]'''\n |votes = Unopposed\n |percentage = ''N/A''\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |\n |title=[[1727 British general election|General election 1727]]: Cumberland (2 seats)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Non Partisan\n |candidate = '''[[Sir James Lowther, 4th Baronet|James Lowther]]'''\n |votes = Unopposed\n |percentage = ''N/A''\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Non Partisan\n |candidate = '''[[Sir Gilfrid Lawson, 6th Baronet|Gilfrid Lawson]]'''\n |votes = Unopposed\n |percentage = ''N/A''\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n*''Note: James Lowther succeeded his brother as [[Lowther Baronets|baronet]] in 1731''\n\n{{Election box begin |\n |title=[[