political party)\n |candidate = '''John Christian Curwen'''\n |votes = 138\n |percentage = 34.5\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Tory\n |candidate = [[George Howard, 6th Earl of Carlisle|George Howard]]\n |votes = 96\n |percentage = 24.0\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cumbria}}\n*[[List of former United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies]]\n*[[Unreformed House of Commons]]\n\n==References==\n* D. Brunton & [[D. H. Pennington]], ''Members of the Long Parliament'' (London: George Allen & Unwin, 1954)\n* Henry Stooks Smith, ''The Parliaments of England from 1715 to 1847'' (2nd edition, edited by [[F. W. S. Craig]] \u2013 Chichester: Parliamentary Reference Publications, 1973)\n* House of Commons records at British History Online [http://www.british-history.ac.uk]\n*{{Rayment-hc|c|6|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cumberland (Uk Parliament Constituency)}}\n[[Category:History of Cumberland]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in North West England (historic)]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies established in 1290]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies disestablished in 1832]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Parliamentary constituency in the United Kingdom, 1801-1832}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency\n|name       = Cumberland\n|type       = County\n|parliament = uk\n|year       = 1290\n|abolished  = 1832\n|elects_howmany = two\n|previous   = \n|next       = [[Cumberland East (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland East]] and [[Cumberland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland West]]\n|}}\n\n'''Cumberland''' is a former [[United Kingdom]] [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliamentary]] [[constituency]]. It was a [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] of the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of England]] then of the [[Parliament of Great Britain]] from 1707 to 1800 and of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] from 1801 to 1832. It was represented by two [[Knights of the Shire]]. It was divided between the constituencies of [[Cumberland East (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland East]] and [[Cumberland West (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumberland West]] in 1832.\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n* ''Constituency created 1290''\n\n===MPs 1290\u20131640===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Parliament!!First member!!Second member\n|-\n| 1301|| [[John Wigton|Sir John Wigton]]||\n|-\n| 1305|| [[John Wigton|Sir John Wigton]]||\n|-\n| 1306|| [[John de Lucy|Sir John de Lucy]]||\n|-\n| 1312|| [[Andrew Harclay, 1st Earl of Carlisle|Andrew Harclay]]||\n|-\n| 1313|| [[John Wigton|Sir John Wigton]]||\n|-\n| 1316|| [[John de Skelton]]||\n|-\n| 1324|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]||\n|-\n| 1325||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1327||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1328||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1331||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1332||[[Robert Parning]]\n|-\n| 1337|| [[Thomas de Skelton]]||\n|-\n| 1342|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]||[[Peter de Tylliol]]\n|-\n| 1344|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]||[[John de Orreton]]\n|-\n| 1345|| [[Hugh de Lowther]]|| [[Henry de Malton]]\n|-\n| 1368|| [[James Pickering]]||\n|-\n| 1377|| [[Richard de Sandys]] ||Sir [[Richard Moubray]]\n|-\n| 1377|| [[John FitzHugh de Lowther]]||\n|-\n| 1378|| [[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Peter Tilliol]]\n|-\n| 1380 (Jan)|| [[William Curwen|Sir William Curwen]]\n|-\n| 1380 (Nov)|| [[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Peter Tilliol]]\n|-\n| 1383|| [[John de Burgham]] ||[[John de Kirby]]\n|-\n| 1385|| [[Richard de Beaulieu|Sir Richard de Beaulieu]]||[[Peter Tilliol (died 1435)|Sir Peter Tilliol]]\n|-\n| 1386||[[Amand Monceaux]]|| [[John Thirlwall]] <ref name = HoP1>{{cite web | url= http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/constituencies/cumberland|title= History of Parliament| accessdate = 2011-09-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1388 (Feb)|| [[John de Derwentwater|Sir John de Derwentwater]]|| [[John Ireby|Sir John Ireby