{"title_page": "Hector Heusghem", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Hector Heusghem\n| image         = Hector Heusghem.jpg\n| full_name     = Hector Heusghem\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1890|02|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Ransart, Belgium]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1982|03|29|1890|02|15}}\n| death_place   = [[Montignies-le-Tilleul]], Belgium\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = 3 stages Tour de France\n}}\n\n'''Hector Heusghem''' ([[Ransart, Belgium|Ransart]], 15 February 1890 \u2013 Montignies-le-Tilleul, 29 March 1982) was a [[Belgian]] [[cyclist]] who finished second in the [[1920 Tour de France|1920]] and [[1921 Tour de France]]. He also won three stages, in 1920 at [[Aix-en-Provence]] and [[Grenoble]], in 1921 in [[Luchon]].\n\nIn 1922, Heusghem took over the [[yellow jersey]] with just three stages to go but on the next day fell foul of the rules. Having broken his frame, he swapped bicycles without permission and received a one-hour penalty that relegated him to fourth and handing the tour to [[Firmin Lambot]].\n\nHector Heusghem was brother of cyclists Pierre-Joseph Heusghem and [[Louis Heusghem]].\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col}}\n;1920\n:[[1920 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stages 8 and 10\n::2nd place overall classification\n;1921\n:[[1921 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 6\n::2nd place overall classification\n;1922\n:[[1922 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::4th place overall classification\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for one day\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cycling Archives|8600}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heusghem, Hector}}\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Belgian Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Charleroi]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hainaut (province)]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Hector Heusghem\n| image         = Hector Heusghem.jpg\n| full_name     = Hector Heusghem\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1890|02|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Ransart, Belgium]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1982|03|29|1890|02|15}}\n| death_place   = [[Montignies-le-Tilleul]], Belgium\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = 3 stages Tour de France\n}}\n\n'''Hector Heusghem''' ([[Ransart, Belgium|Ransart]], 15 February 1890 &mdash; Montignies-le-Tilleul, 29 March 1982) was a [[Belgian]] [[cyclist]] who finished second in the [[1920 Tour de France|1920]] and [[1921 Tour de France]]. He also won three stages, in 1920 at [[Aix-en-Provence]] and [[Grenoble]], in 1921 in [[Luchon]].\n\nIn 1922, Heusghem took over the [[yellow jersey]] with just three stages to go but on the next day fell foul of the rules. Having broken his frame, he swapped bicycles without permission and received a one-hour penalty that relegated him to fourth and handing the tour to [[Firmin Lambot]].\n\nHector Heusghem was brother of cyclists Pierre-Joseph Heusghem and [[Louis Heusghem]].\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col}}\n;1920\n:[[1920 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stages 8 and 10\n::2nd place overall classification\n;1921\n:[[1921 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 6\n::2nd place overall classification\n;1922\n:[[1922 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::4th place overall classification\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for one day\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cycling Archives|8600}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heusghem, Hector}}\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Belgian Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Charleroi]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hainaut (province)]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hector_Heusghem"}
{"title_page": "Peter Russo (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian lawyer and politician in Queensland}}\n{{about|the Australian politician|the fictional American politician|House of Cards (U.S. TV series)#Cast and characters}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name = Peter Russo\n| honorific-suffix = [[Parliament of Queensland|MP]]\n| image           =Peter Russo MP Member for Toohey.jpg \n| assembly        = Queensland Legislative\n| constituency_AM = [[Electoral district of Sunnybank|Sunnybank]]\n| term_start      = 31 January 2015\n| term_end        = 25 November 2017\n| predecessor     = [[Mark Stewart (politician)|Mark Stewart]]\n| successor       = ''Seat abolished''\n| constituency_AM2 = [[Electoral district of Toohey|Toohey]]\n| assembly2       = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start2     = 25 November 2017\n| term_end2       = \n| predecessor2    = ''New seat''\n| successor2      = \n| party           = [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1955|9|13}}\n| birth_place     = [[Townsville, Queensland]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| spouse          = \n| children        = \n| residence       = \n| profession      = Lawyer\n| religion        = \n| website         = \n| university      = \n}}\n'''Peter Samuel Russo''' (born 13 September 1955) is an Australian politician. He is the [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor Party]] member for [[Electoral district of Toohey|Toohey]] (formerly [[Electoral district of Sunnybank|Sunnybank]]) in the [[Queensland Legislative Assembly]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/sunn/|title=Sunnybank|work=Queensland Election 2015|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|last=Green|first=Antony|authorlink=Antony Green}}</ref>\n\nRusso is currently the Chair of the Legal Affairs and Community Safety Committee. He has previously served as the Acting Chair of the Parliamentary Crime and Corruption Committee and Chair of the Finance and Administration Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/current/list/MemberDetails?ID=2411213250|title=Mr Peter Russo|last=|first=|date=|website=Queensland Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to being elected, Russo was the Principal of Russo Lawyers and is admitted as a solicitor of the Supreme Courts of [[Supreme Court of Queensland|Queensland]], [[Supreme Court of New South Wales|New South Wales]], and [[Supreme Court of Western Australia|Western Australia]] and the [[High Court of Australia]]. He holds a Master of Laws from the [[Queensland University of Technology]]. He has been admitted for over 30 years, with particular focus in the area of criminal law. He is a past member of the Queensland Law Society Criminal Law Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://russolawyers.com.au/our-team/peter-russo/|title=Peter Russo|last=|first=|date=|website=Russo Lawyers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was named ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper\u2019s \"Australian of the Year\" in 2007. He has been involved in many high profile cases, including representing Dr [[Mohamed Haneef]] in 2007 and 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/haneef-released-as-charges-dropped-20070728-gdqq0u.html|title=Haneef released as charges dropped|last=Coorey|first=Phillip|date=28 July 2007|website=Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|Peter Russo (politician)}}{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-qld}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Stewart (politician)|Mark Stewart]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Sunnybank|Sunnybank]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-non|reason=Abolished}}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Toohey|Toohey]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{QldCurrentMPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russo, Peter}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queensland Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Australian lawyers]]\n[[Category:People from Townsville]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Australia-Labor-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian lawyer and politician in Queensland}}\n{{about|the Australian politician|the fictional American politician|House of Cards (U.S. TV series)#Cast and characters}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name = Peter Russo\n| honorific-suffix = [[Parliament of Queensland|MP]]\n| image           =Peter Russo MP Member for Toohey.jpg \n| assembly        = Queensland Legislative\n| constituency_AM = [[Electoral district of Sunnybank|Sunnybank]]\n| term_start      = 31 January 2015\n| term_end        = 25 November 2017\n| predecessor     = [[Mark Stewart (politician)|Mark Stewart]]\n| successor       = ''Seat abolished''\n| constituency_AM2 = [[Electoral district of Toohey|Toohey]]\n| assembly2       = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start2     = 25 November 2017\n| term_end2       = \n| predecessor2    = ''New seat''\n| successor2      = \n| party           = [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1955|9|13}}\n| birth_place     = [[Townsville, Queensland]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| spouse          = \n| children        = \n| residence       = \n| profession      = Lawyer\n| religion        = \n| website         = \n| university      = \n}}\n'''Peter Samuel Russo''' (born 13 September 1955) is an Australian politician. He is the [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor Party]] member for [[Electoral district of Toohey|Toohey]] (formerly [[Electoral district of Sunnybank|Sunnybank]]) in the [[Queensland Legislative Assembly]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/sunn/|title=Sunnybank|work=Queensland Election 2015|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|last=Green|first=Antony|authorlink=Antony Green}}</ref>\n\nRusso is currently the Chair of the Legal Affairs and Community Safety Committee. He has previously served as the Acting Chair of the Parliamentary Crime and Corruption Committee and Chair of the Finance and Administration Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/current/list/MemberDetails?ID=2411213250|title=Mr Peter Russo|last=|first=|date=|website=Queensland Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to being elected, Russo was the Principal of Russo Lawyers and is admitted as a solicitor of the Supreme Courts of [[Supreme Court of Queensland|Queensland]], [[Supreme Court of New South Wales|New South Wales]], and [[Supreme Court of Western Australia|Western Australia]] and the [[High Court of Australia]]. He holds a Master of Laws from the [[Queensland University of Technology]]. He has been admitted for over 30 years, with particular focus in the area of criminal law. He is a past member of the Queensland Law Society Criminal Law Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://russolawyers.com.au/our-team/peter-russo/|title=Peter Russo|last=|first=|date=|website=Russo Lawyers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was named [[The Australian]] newspaper\u2019s Australian of the Year in 2007. He has been involved in many high profile cases, including representing Dr [[Mohamed Haneef]] in 2007 and 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/haneef-released-as-charges-dropped-20070728-gdqq0u.html|title=Haneef released as charges dropp